<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i2.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-13-22-17-04-011.jpg?fit=1024%2C580&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35840"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35841,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-13-22-19-03-392.jpg?fit=1024%2C580&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35841"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>They even refused to cooperate with the court.  In fact, they weren't even prepared to work with each other to figure it out, if you can believe that. As we all probably know very well, courts force people to do all kinds of outrageous and redundant things, but when it came to figuring out who owned the largest fresh produce company in the world, it just wasn't humanly possible.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35843,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-13-22-30-06-383.jpg?fit=1024%2C423&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35843"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Just  to refresh your memories: 70% of the prime brokerage industry is controlled by 6 <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="massive corporations (opens in a new tab)" href="https://interactiveswingtrades.com/2019/11/18/flash-fact-six-brokers-control-roughly-70-of-the-prime-brokerage-industry-hfalert-com/" target="_blank">massive corporations</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":37229,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large"><img src="https://interactiveswingtrades.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-01-26-16-43-13-813-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-37229"/><figcaption>https://www.hfalert.com/rankings/rankings.pl?Q=149</figcaption></figure></div>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"red-yellow-background-link"} -->
<p class="red-yellow-background-link">And they don't only rely on the DTCC for processing trades; they have their own clearing departments, and some of them are massive. For example, in the year 2000, Goldman Sachs paid <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="US$6.5 billion (opens in a new tab)" href="https://archive.is/PsoPk#selection-1925.0-1925.331" target="_blank">US$6.5 billion</a> for Spear, Leeds &amp; Kellogg, L.P. -- a securities clearing, execution, and market making firm  with origins that go back as far as 1932.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"customFontSize":40,"className":"cursive-background-image-2"} -->
<p style="font-size:40px" class="cursive-background-image-2">(Wall Street Journal) "<em>In addition, <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Spear claims to run the country's largest clearing business by number of stock and options trades cleared.</strong></span> Acquiring Spear vaults Goldman into the leading ranks of clearing brokers alongside Bear Stearns Cos ., Merrill Lynch, and Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette (now being acquired by Credit Suisse First Boston</em>".<br><a href="https://archive.is/1AE1R#selection-2167.0-2183.13">https://archive.is/1AE1R#selection-2167.0-2183.13</a></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"customFontSize":40,"className":"cursive-background-image-2"} -->
<p style="font-size:40px" class="cursive-background-image-2"><em>(Bloomberg) "Although trading firms are often shunned by investors because of volatile earnings, Paulson called Spear Leeds a profit machine that would smooth out Goldman’s results. He said the firm has earned money every month for the last nine years, and that <strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">clearing--settling trades for other firms for a fee--is its biggest profit center".</span></strong></em><br><a href="https://archive.is/PsoPk#selection-1925.0-1928.0">https://archive.is/PsoPk#selection-1925.0-1928.0</a></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>From Morgan Stanley's Annual Report, 12/31/18</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":37746,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://www.secinfo.com/d14D5a.y1yn8.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-22-20-50-02-327.jpg?fit=1024%2C418&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-37746"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>They spent billions on these services..</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35893,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i2.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-14-03-44-08-601.jpg?fit=1024%2C503&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35893"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>JPM's 2018 Annual Report</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":37744,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://www.secinfo.com/dJ5e.y1p.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img src="https://i1.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-22-20-48-47-074.jpg?fit=1024%2C418&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-37744"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>All of these massive corporations have their own clearing divisions -- obviously..Yet when it came to finding out who the actual owners were, they just said it wasn't worth their time, and specifically, that it would require a, quote:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>"<em>Herculean effort</em> " for which "<em>The journey down the rabbit hole would require mapping the entire warren</em>"</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35896,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i1.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-14-03-33-23-184.jpg?fit=1024%2C555&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35896"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Interesting choice of words..</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><br>Guess who the courts told Dole to pay first? The banks.  Remember, they are the real record holders.  They then distributed the merger consideration to their beneficial owners.  </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35847,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i1.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-13-22-57-36-306.jpg?fit=1024%2C427&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35847"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35848,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i2.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-13-22-58-01-599.jpg?fit=1024%2C427&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35848"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The reason why the courts chose the banks as the ones who would receive the merger consideration was because they had access to all the records, and specifically: <br><br><br>"<em>the terms on which shares are borrowed</em> ".</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35855,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i1.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-13-23-07-55-634.jpg?fit=1024%2C543&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35855"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>If that's the case then what was the problem? You really think these mega-banks can't keep track of who owns what for 3 days? <br><br> Common, you're smarter than that.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35884,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-14-02-32-51-403.jpg?fit=1024%2C490&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35884"/></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Sometimes it helps if you simplify things, so let's do that.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":35885,"width":944,"height":435,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2020-02-12-18-25-30-399.jpg?fit=1024%2C473&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35885" width="944" height="435"/></figure></div>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>How would reconcile this?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Let's say there was a merger and somebody bought that one share, but there was two shares in circulation at the time.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>How would you reconcile that??</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The broker would give the money back to the person who bought the shares from the short seller, then give the shares back to the original owner. That shouldn't be complicated for these massive corporations, and if it is, we've got a serious problem.   </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"red-yellow-background-link"} -->
<p class="red-yellow-background-link">Why should we believe anything these people have to say at this point? The largest bank in America is a<a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://wallstreetonparade.com/2019/11/jamie-dimon-tells-60-minutes-hes-a-patriot-theres-good-reason-to-think-hes-a-crime-boss/" target="_blank"> two-time felon</a>. Meaning, the corporation itself was indicted -- not the people who run the corporation, but <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://archive.is/dmx60" target="_blank">the corporation</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"blue-yellow-background-link"} -->
<p class="blue-yellow-background-link">It makes no sense, but that's what happened.  The guy who headed this corporation through both of these indictments wasn't even fired; he still sits on the board, and he's still the CEO.  <br><br>Here's the worst part.  While his firm was being investigated by the New York Fed, he was <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="sat on their board (opens in a new tab)" href="https://wallstreetonparade.com/2019/12/the-new-york-fed-is-keeping-jpmorgans-secrets-close-to-its-chest/" target="_blank">sitting on their board</a> the entire time -- the only institution in America that is legally allowed the <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.investopedia.com/ask/answers/06/openmarketoperations.asp" target="_blank">manipulate the daily interest rate of a government treasury bond</a>.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"blue-yellow-background-link"} -->
<p class="blue-yellow-background-link">You definitely wouldn't want the wrong person in control of something like that, because technically all they would have to do is instruct the New York Fed to buy their treasuries at inflated prices during their intraday Open Market Operations, repeating the cycle over and over again for years on end.  </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>They’ve already been caught rigging the <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="Municipal Bond Market (opens in a new tab)" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190908142736/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/the-scam-wall-street-learned-from-the-mafia-190232/" target="_blank">Municipal Bond Market</a>, so would it really be all that surprising if it came out one day that these mega-banks were also rigging the federal government bond market too.. <br><br>Think about it this way: from a legal standpoint, J.P. Morgan is technically considered a <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="repeat offenders (opens in a new tab)" href="https://jpmadoff.com/victims/" target="_blank">repeat offender</a>, and what do repeat offenders usually continue doing? Committing more crimes -- not unless they are forced to stop, at least -- but unfortunately that's not what appears to be happening, and this is clearly evidenced in the fact that not one <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="high level corporate executive (opens in a new tab)" href="https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/frontline/film/untouchables/" target="_blank">high level corporate executive</a> was sent to jail during the Great Recession.  Apparently they don't even investigate these massive corporations, let alone get them in trouble when they break the law; something that was revealed by <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="Frontline  (opens in a new tab)" href="https://archive.is/1woMy#selection-375.0-406.0" target="_blank">Frontline </a>in 2013.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"blue-yellow-background-link"} -->
<p class="blue-yellow-background-link">When you break it all down, the New York Fed is no different than any other government contractor, and what do government contractors usually do best? Rip off government. Why? Because politicians tend to lack basic knowledge about the industry, or worse, they can be corrupt.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"blue-yellow-background-link"} -->
<p class="blue-yellow-background-link">This is a big problem in construction industry.  A recent example being the Sturgeon refinery in Canada; a project that ended up costing taxpayers<a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" 8 times more (opens in a new tab)" href="https://www.oilsandsmagazine.com/news/2017/12/14/sturgeon-refinery-produces-first-diesel" target="_blank"> 8 times more</a> than a similarly sized refinery built by the private sector, and when all was said and done, went on to become the <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.albertaoilmagazine.com/2014/11/high-price-adding-value/" target="_blank">most expensive oil refinery ever built</a> -- and by a long shot. It produces a whopping 40,250 bbl/day.  <br><br>The CEO of a two time felon ("<em><a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)" href="https://jpmadoff.com/victims/" target="_blank">The Company</a></em> ") sat on the New York Feds board while the two time felon ("<em><a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)" href="https://jpmadoff.com/victims/" target="_blank">The Company</a></em> ") was being investigated. <br><br>Think about that for second.  </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"id":35973,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><a href="https://perma.cc/ZE6L-BNMC" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/stocktrades.exchange/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/bandicam-2019-11-27-18-20-34-356.jpg?fit=1024%2C394&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-35973"/></a></figure>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The image below lists all the biggest players in the "tri-party" repo market; another one of Wall Streets industry terms that they use to describe a collateralized&nbsp;short-term loan. The "tri" is just meant to signify that there is a clearinghouse involved.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As you can see, they loan money to themselves; money that they usually get from the fed.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:image {"align":"center","id":41626,"width":842,"height":509,"sizeSlug":"large"} -->
<div class="wp-block-image"><figure class="aligncenter size-large is-resized"><a href="https://www.mckinsey.com/~/media/mckinsey/dotcom/client_service/financial%20services/latest%20thinking/reports/global_corporate_and_investment_banking_an_agenda_for_change.ashx" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img src="https://i2.wp.com/interactiveswingtrades.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/bandicam-2020-03-11-04-22-56-584.jpg?fit=1024%2C620&amp;ssl=1" alt="" class="wp-image-41626" width="842" height="509"/></a><figcaption>https://archive.is/BTeN8</figcaption></figure></div>
<!-- /wp:image -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As of today, money market funds are able to borrow from the fed at 1.5%.  To put that into perspective, if they loan this money out to the public at 6%, their margins will increase by a factor 300%.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Just imagine if Dole's margins went up that much?  </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"className":"red-yellow-background-link"} -->
<p class="red-yellow-background-link"><br><br>Does the New York Fed assist these banks with their fraudulent activity? Who knows. What we do know is that the CEO of a twice convicted felon ("<em><a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label=" (opens in a new tab)" href="https://jpmadoff.com/victims/" target="_blank">The Company</a></em> ") sat on the board of the New York Fed  while they were being investigated; an organization that <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="fired one of their key bank supervisors (opens in a new tab)" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/the-carmen-segarra-tapes" target="_blank">fired one of their key banking supervisors</a> for <a rel="noreferrer noopener" aria-label="daring to suggest (opens in a new tab)" href="https://www.thisamericanlife.org/536/the-secret-recordings-of-carmen-segarra" target="_blank">daring to suggest</a> that one of their member banks didn't have a clear conflict of interest policy, and this was not long after its member banks had essentially pumped and dumped the entire country of America -- the largest economy in world history -- into,  as Ben Bernanke put it, <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://interactiveswingtrades.com/2019/09/18/quote-in-2009-ben-bernanke-said-the-2008-financial-crisis-was-worse-than-the-great-depression/" target="_blank">the worst financial crisis in America history</a>. <br><br>The member bank's argument was that they were <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://archive.is/sFmxG#selection-253.0-256.0" target="_blank">not a "depository institution"</a>, and thus did not fall under the scope her investigation -- even though they were being regulated by the New York Fed (which regulates depository institutions) and had recently gained access to the Federal Reserve's discount window; something that was unprecedented for an investment bank at that time.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
<hr class="wp-block-separator"/>
<!-- /wp:separator -->

<!-- wp:separator -->
